I"e<ol>
  <li>
    <p>But you can get through the days there without trouble, once you have formed habits. And since habits are precisely what our town encourages, all is <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="for the best - (to say a particular event may seem bad now, but might have a good result later)"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(也许不是件坏事/终究有好处)</code></b>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Nevertheless, there still exist towns and countries where people have now and then an <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="a slight knowledge or vague notion"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">inkling</code></b> of something different. In general, it doesn’t change their lives. Still, they have had an <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="\ ˌin-tə-ˈmā-shən \ an indirect, usually subtle suggestion, indication, or hint 迹象"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">intimation</code></b>, and that’s <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="so much to the good - (to the good - generally helpful)"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(带来很大的好处)</code></b>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The passions of the young are violent and short-lived; <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="the vices of older men seldom range beyond"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(老年人的恶习不外乎...)</code></b> an addiction to bowling, to banquets and “socials,” or clubs where large sums <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="change hands on the fall of a card"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(在一张牌的起落之间已然易主)</code></b>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Certainly nothing is commoner nowadays than to see people working from morn till night and then proceeding to <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="fritter away at card-tables"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(在牌桌上挥霍)</code></b>, in cafés and in <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="small-talk"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(闲扯)</code></b> what time is left for living.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The men and women consume one another rapidly in what is called “the act of love,” or else <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="settle down to a mild habit of conjugality - (conjugality - \ ˌkän-​ji-​ˈga-​lə-​tē , -​jü-​ \)"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(安于平淡的婚姻生活)</code></b>. We seldom find <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="a mean between these extremes"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(两个极端中的中间点)</code></b>. That, too, is not exceptional.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Being ill is never agreeable, but there are towns that <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="stand by you"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(继续忠于某人/支持某人)</code></b>, so to speak, when you are sick; in which you can, <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="after a fashion"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(not very much, 不很好、马马虎虎、勉强凑合)</code></b>, <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="let yourself go"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(to behave in a very free and open way 这里是放松些的意思)</code></b>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>In our little town (is this, one wonders, an effect of the climate?) all three are done <b data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="on much the same lines"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">________(similarly)</code></b>, with the same feverish yet casual air. The truth is that everyone is bored, and devotes himself to cultivating habits.</p>
  </li>
</ol>
